e" tabindex="0"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden"><div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert wrap-break-word w-full dark markdown-new-styling"><p data-start="0" data-end="86">Excellent! 🎉 <strong data-start="14" data-end="62">You have completed the SQL analysis section.</strong> That's a big milestone.</p>
<p data-start="88" data-end="123">The monthly sales trend shows that:</p>
<ul data-start="124" data-end="328">
<li data-start="124" data-end="156">
<p data-start="126" data-end="156">Sales fluctuate across months.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="157" data-end="266">
<p data-start="159" data-end="266"><strong data-start="159" data-end="167">2017</strong> had the highest monthly sales, with <strong data-start="204" data-end="229">November (118,447.82)</strong> being the peak month in the dataset.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="267" data-end="328">
<p data-start="269" data-end="328">This chart will look great as a <strong data-start="301" data-end="315">Line Chart</strong> in Power BI.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="330" data-end="333">
<h1 data-start="335" data-end="393" class="PDq2pG_selectionAnchorContainer" style="--targeted-action-anchor-block-start: 0px; --targeted-action-anchor-inline-start: 0px; --targeted-action-anchor-inline-size: 599.487548828125px; --targeted-action-anchor-block-size: 31.99999237060547px;">Before moving to Power BI, let's organize your SQL file.<span aria-hidden="true" class="PDq2pG_selectionAnchor"></span></h1>
<p data-start="395" data-end="477">Save all your queries in a file named <strong data-start="433" data-end="457"><code data-start="435" data-end="455">Sales_Analysis.sql</code></strong>. It should include:</p>
