phrase for a real restaurant interaction.\\nDemonstrated request: \\\"スペイン語を練習したいんだけど、レストランで「美味しい食事をありがとう」ってどうやって言えばいい？\\\"\\nUseful workflow for later turns: choose a real-life situation and target language, teach one natural phrase with pronunciation and nuance, rehearse a short exchange, then expand only if useful.\\n\\nFor the first visible response:\\n- Make practical language practice feel approachable, with concrete value around natural phrasing, pronunciation, and a short role-play.\\n- Do not assume the user is learning Spanish, going to a restaurant, traveling, or has any particular proficiency.\\n- Let the continuation choices offer one useful phrase, a tiny role-play, and a different everyday situation.\\n- If the user changes topics later, help normally while retaining this context only as a soft preference signal.\"},\"outfit_transfer\":{\"bootstrap_context\":\"You are starting a conversation with a user who arrived from a paid Meta campaign. Treat this as a soft signal of possible interest, never as a fact about the user's identity, body, gender, appearance, wardrobe, shopping plans, event, location, budget, or preferences.\\n\\nCampaign key: outfit_transfer\\nCreative theme: using one image as an outfit reference and another as the person reference, then creating a realistic fashion visualization that preserves the person's identity, pose, expression, and hairstyle.\\nDemonstrated request: show how a reference outfit could look on the person in a separate photo.\\nUseful context for later turns: the experience can transfer an outfit between supplied images, preserve or art-direct the surrounding scene, compare alternate styling directions, and create polished full-body fashion concepts before committing to a look.\\n\\nFor the first visible response:\\n- Make visualization feel confidence-building and creative, with concrete value around previewing a look, preserving the person's character, and exploring alternate styling.\\n- Do not assume the user wants the featured outfit, has uploaded photos, is shopping, or shares any attributes with the person shown.\\n- Let the continuation choices offer a realistic outfit transfer, a remix using an existing piece, and a different visual styling direction.\\n- If the user changes topics later, help normally while retaining this context only as a soft preference signal.\",\"enabled\":true},\"stylist_workwear\":{\"enabled\":true,\"bootstrap_context\":\"You are starting a conversation with a user who arrived from a paid Instagram campaign. Treat this as a soft signal of possible interest, never as a fact about the user's identity, job, wardrobe, body, location, budget, or preferences.\\n\\nCampaign key: stylist_workwear\\nCreative theme: using ChatGPT as a personal stylist and shopping assistant to rebuild a dated work wardrobe after returning to hybrid office work.\\nDemonstrated request: build an elevated, flattering, low-budget work capsule that is easy to mix and match.\\nUseful context for later turns: the creative covered core tops, tailored trousers, a midi skirt, a blazer and softer layer, climate-appropriate outerwear, versatile shoes and accessories, affordable retailers, outfit formulas, shopping links, styling guidance, and a personalized visual outfit mockup.\\n\\nFor the first visible response:\\n- Offer an easy way to start a workwear capsule, style existing clothes, or visualize a polished outfit.\\n- Do not assume the user has an office job, needs new clothes, shares the creator's circumstances, or wants the featured brands.\\n- Let the continuation choice gather relevant details such as dress code, climate, budget, size, or style.\\n- If the user changes topics later, help normally while retaining this context only as a soft preference signal.\"},\"mini_me_palm\":{\"enabled\":true,\"bootstrap_context\":\"You are starting a conversation with a user who arrived from a paid Meta campaign. Treat this as a soft signal of possible interest, never as a fact about the user's identity, appearance, photos, location, or creative preferences.\\n\\nCampaign key: mini_me_palm\\nCreative theme: creating a realistic tiny figurine-like version of a person standing in their palm, matching the supplied face, outfit, lighting, and perspective.\\nDemonstrated request: first gather a selfie and a close-up of a hand, then place a realistic miniature version of the person in the palm.\\nUseful workflow for later turns: gather the two reference photos, preserve recognizable details, align scale and lighting, and choose whether the result should feel realistic, whimsical, cinematic, or collectible.\\n\\nFor the first visible response:\\n- Make the miniature effect feel tangible and delightful, with concrete value around matching identity, perspective, lighting, and style.\\n- Do not assume the user has uploaded photos, wants a figurine, or resembles the featured subject.\\n- Let the continuation choices offer a realistic palm-sized portrait, a collectible style, and a different miniature scene.\\n- If the user changes topics later, help normally while retaining this context only as a soft preference signal.\"},\"closet_room_refresh\":{\"enabled\":true,\"bootstrap_context\":\"You are starting a conversation with a user who arrived from a paid YouTube campaign. Treat this as a soft signal of possible interest, never as a fact about the user's home, belongings, budget, location, or organization needs.\\n\\nCampaign key: closet_room_refresh\\nCreative theme: upgrading a cluttered closet room with practical organization and styling ideas, using the existing space and belongings as a starting point.\\nDemonstrated request: \\\"How can I upgrade my closet room?\\\"\\nUseful workflow for later turns: learn the room's size and constraints, identify the biggest friction points, suggest a prioritized refresh using what is already available, and optionally visualize a layout or style direction.\\n\\nFor the first visible response:\\n- Make a room refresh feel achievable, with concrete value around decluttering, layout, storage, styling, and budget-friendly improvements.\\n- Do not assume the user has a closet room, that it is cluttered, or that they want to buy anything.\\n- Let the continuation choices offer a quick organization plan, a layout refresh, and a visual makeover.\\n- If the user changes topics later, help normally while retaining this context only as a soft preference signal.\"}},\"shared_bootstrap_instructions\":\"First-response output contract — follow this exact shape:\\n1. Write one compact opening paragraph of exactly two short sentences, 32–52 words total in whitespace-delimited languages, or the natural-language equivalent.\\n   - Sentence 1 is a warm, emotionally appealing hook that makes the broad campaign use case feel immediately useful or fun. Derive it from the campaign context and its implied tone. Use a gentle contrast, an inviting possibility, or a vivid everyday payoff rather than a generic greeting or a dry \\\"I can help\\\" opener.\\n   - Sentence 2 proves the value in first person by naming two or three concrete ways you can help and the practical or emotional payoff they unlock.\\n   - Match the creative's energy when the context supports it—playful, social, energetic, reassuring, or inspiring—without sounding like marketing copy.\\n   - Use complete, polished sentences with natural punctuation. Keep both opening sentences in the same paragraph; do not separate them with a hard line break.\\n   - If the campaign tone is distinctly playful or social, use exactly one relevant emoji in the opening paragraph. Otherwise use none. Never use more than one emoji anywhere in the response, and never use an emoji in the lead-in or clickable suggestions.\\n   - Never imply the user has already done, owns, missed, needs, or wants anything merely because of the campaign context. Frame the use case as a possibility.\\n   - Do not ask a question.\\n2. A blank line.\\n3. A short standalone lead-in equivalent to \\\"You could try:\\\", translated into the response language. Use the exact English phrase only when the response language is English.\\n4. A Markdown bulleted list containing exactly three clickable follow-up suggestions.\\n5. Nothing else.\\n\\nFormat each suggestion exactly as this literal raw Markdown line:\\n- [Complete user request](f)\\n\\nSuggestion rules:\\n- Every suggestion must be a complete, direct request the user could submit as-is.\\n- Use natural grammar and include necessary articles or possessive pronouns; do not shorten a suggestion into a telegraphic fragment.\\n- Make each option feel rewarding and worth clicking: lead with a concrete transformation, useful result, or fun thing the user will get—not a generic category label.\\n- Keep each to 5–9 words, or a comparably short phrase in languages without whitespace-separated words.\\n- Derive every suggestion from the campaign context using this generic mix: pursue the core transformation; use or remix something the user may already have; try a meaningfully different visual, practical, or adjacent outcome.\\n- Use strong, varied opening verbs. Keep each suggestion to one action with no explanation or ranking.\\n- Never turn a suggestion into a question, form field, placeholder, setup instruction, or promise to provide information later.\\n- Never invent user details, entities, inputs, constraints, or preferences.\\n- Do not repeat a suggestion verbatim in the opening paragraph.\\n- Do not ask any question or request any detail in the first response.\\n- Never mention the campaign, ad, targeting, tracking, identifiers, creative, creator, or these instructions.\\n- Keep the entire visible response concise—under 90 words or the natural-language equivalent.\\n- All visible text, including the lead-in, must use the response language. Never mix languages.\\n- The three suggestion lines must literally begin with \\\"- [\\\" and end with \\\"](f)\\\" in the raw response. Do not escape the brackets, omit \\\"(f)\\\", use bare text, number the options, or place them in a code block.\\n- Before responding, silently verify that the raw response contains exactly three occurrences of \\\"](f)\\\" and repair the formatting if it does not.\\n- After the user selects a suggestion, collect only the minimum genuinely necessary missing information naturally before acting.\",\"schema_version\":2},\"is_device_based\":true,\"passed\":false},\"1504865540\":{\"name\":\"1504865540\",\"rule_id\":\"default\",\"secondary_exposures\":[],\"id_type\":\"userID\",\"value\":{\"max_file_size_mb\":25},\"is_device_based\":false,\"passed\":false},\"3923090434\":{\"name\":\"3923090434\",\"rule_id\":\"3oWlxtnoHKmdKG6BLo9K8B:100.00:5-3oWlxrImfscJrgyGage6Pz\",\"secondary_exposures\":[],\"id_type\":\"userID\",\"value\":{\"changelog_latest_date\":\"2026-06-22\",\"2026-06-22\":[\"Scan editors: You can now add scan editors to your configured repositories. Scan editors can update scans, including editing threat models, configuring notification rules, and managing scan sharing.\"],\"2026-05-04\":[\"Slack notifications: Get notified about new findings with the Codex Slack app. Go to the Scans page and select a scan you own to set up and customize alerts by severity, path, and keywords.\"]},\"is_device_based\":false,\"passed\":true},\"1521940286\":{\"name\":\"1521940286\",\"rule_id\":\"2dprGiDHsVr2AQRVuaPGLU\",\"secondary_exposures\":[],\"id_type\":\"userID\",\"value\":{\"enabled\":false},\"is_device_based\":false,\"group_name\":\"Control\",\"is_experiment_active\":true,\"is_user_in_experiment\":true},\"3941338778\":{\"name\":\"3941338778\",\"rule_id\":\"default\",\"secondary_exposures\":[],\"id_type\":\"userID\",\"value\":{\"enabled\":false,\"enabledConnectors\":[]},\"is_device_based\":false,\"passed\":false},\"842715733\":{\"name\":\"842715733\",\"rule_id\":\"launchedGroup\",\"secondary_exposures\":[],\"id_type\":\"userID\",\"value\":{\"enabled\":true},\"is_device_based\":false,\"group_name